Oct 7 2007 	Convenient Location Good Staff	Fraser Place Queens Gate is in a great location for access to sightseeing -- one block from the Gloucester Road Tube station which services the Picadilly, District and Circle lines that access many points of interest directly. Get a day pass and ride the Tube (and buses) all day -- very, very easy even on your first day there. The aparthotel itself is relatively quiet; not a luxury accomodation by any stretch, but the apartments are decent, if a bit plain (they'd do well to get some decorations on the wall just to brighten things up a bit). I believe that Fraser Hospitality recently took over this property, so they are still in the process of renovation (a few back hallways had rolled up carpeting, etc. nothing obtrusive, though). We had a decent-sized one-bedroom apartment (G03) on the second floor up a private set of stairs. Definitely roomy by London standards. While there was no stove (only a single hotplate), there was a microwave, refrigerator and kitchenware which made it easier to save money by not eating out for every meal (London's not really known for their great cuisine anyway!) The bathroom was adequate to smallish in terms of size; however we had plumbing problems at the beginning and end of our trip. The beginning of the trip we had no hot water in the shower, but the hotel promptly sent up their maintenance guy to fix things. The morning we were leaving, we woke up to no water at all (including the toilet). The hotel allowed us to use another empty apartment's bathroom (G06 on the first floor - a large studio which had a HUGE bathroom and nice looking apartment) to shower, so, while inconvenient, the hotel promptly responded to our needs. Negatives:* Plumbing issues for our apartment, but all was remedied as quickly as they could.* Plain, mildly gloomy apartment (we looked out on a brick wall from both rooms).* No clock in the room (ask for one and they'll provide one for you, though).Positives:* Location, definitely. Easy to get around the city and feels safe. Plenty of places to eat and change money.* Staff is friendly, always accessible and very responsive.* More room than the average hotel in London, but similar pricing to mid-range hotels. Check their website for special prices.All in all, I think we'd stay there again despite the few issues we had. The staff is very nice and the location can't be beat for the price.	
Aug 4 2007 	Overall a great place to stay	Our family of four (including two teenage boys) stayed in a one bedroom super deluxe apartment at the end of July. We initially searched a ton of London hotels looking for a quadruple room, to no avail, so finally chose to go the apartment route and we are very glad we did! The apartment was clean and modern with a small kitchenette, sofa bed and table &amp; chairs in the living area. The pictures on the hotel website are accurate. The building is currently being refurbished on the outside; however our room was fully remodeled and surprisingly even had air conditioning. The air conditioning unit worked well initially but after awhile made odd sounds so we turned it off (it really wasn’t necessary anyway due to the mild temperatures, we primarily used it so we didn’t have to keep the windows open at night and hear the street traffic). The only negative experienced was that while a hairdryer was provided, it could not be used in the bathroom (which contained a shaver-only plug). Normally I wouldn't mind this, but considering there were no mirrors within range of a plug for the hairdryer it ended up being quite inconvenient! The housekeeping staff was kind enough to make the sofa bed more comfortable by providing an extra duvet to be used on top of the mattress. Breakfast was just fine, mostly pastries, donuts and fruit (try to get breakfast included in your room rate if possible). The location of the apartments is outstanding, a 5 minute walk from the Gloucester Road Tube station in a beautiful residential area of South Kensington. We either walked or took the tube everywhere! The front desk clerks were very friendly and helpful. Internet access is available for a small fee (unless you plan on being on the internet a lot, purchase only a small amount of hours as it is for cumulative usage over the period of time it is used rather than expiring in a set period of hours). Overall, I would recommend Fraser Place Queens Gate to families who need extra space and want to be near a tube stop in a very safe, pleasant area of London.	
